                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d606">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.24 Raw Materials/69: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                        Minister in the Netherlands</hi> (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gordon</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-04-13T19:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 13, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>23. Your 37, April 12, 3 p.m. For your information and guidance, the Department
                    is reemphasizing to the press the fact that under the proposal certain American
                    surplus commodities would be offered in exchange for strategic materials only if
                    foreign governments would agree to hold the stocks acquired as reserves for
                    national emergencies, with adequate safeguards against the release of any part
                    of such stocks to commercial markets. Because of these features, we feel that
                    this proposal does not run contrary to our commercial policies and is quite
                    different from commercial barter deals. These transactions would be entirely
                    apart from commercial markets and should not influence them.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hull</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
